WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Hi everyone, my name is Michael Chirico. I'm currently a data scientist at Google and I've

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.840
been contributing to DataTable in my free time for several years. I'm here to talk to

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:17.480
you today about how to add translations to your R packages.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:21.520
So why would you want to add translations to your R packages? We're very blessed in

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:26.040
the R community to have a very global community. Just from a snapshot that we see in the R

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:30.920
ladies directory and in the RStudio community survey, we see that the R community is a very

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:37.240
global one in all the continents with usage from all over the world. So by the time that

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:41.360
you release your package, it will start to be used by people and their native language

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:48.480
is not English. And a lot of package developers themselves, their native language is not English.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.840
And kind of motivated by this and over the years seeing error messages reported on the

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:57.599
DataTable issue tracker from people whose R session was clearly not in English, we took

00:00:57.599 --> 00:01:04.919
up the challenge of trying to add translations to DataTable. We landed on doing Chinese and

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:10.279
we got together a team of over 20 translators to work on this. It ended up being kind of

00:01:10.279 --> 00:01:13.879
a monumental undertaking because DataTable is a pretty old package. Coming with that,

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:20.199
there's over 1400 error messages in DataTable itself. I think typical packages have less

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:27.279
than 100. A lot of packages have less than 20 even. So 1400 actually took quite a lot

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:33.040
of time to figure out even how to go about translating. And I'd love to have time to

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:38.680
thank individually all those people. It's really an honor to have been a part of it.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:42.480
But just while we have time in this short time, to thank Hongyuan Zhao, Zhiyang, and

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:46.480
Guangcheng Yu who really helped get the team together and get it over the finish line to

00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:53.120
The whole time I was working on this, I was kind of taken aback by how much friction there

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:58.000
is in the process. There's a lot of pain points in having to learn a whole new language, which

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.559
is this language of get text and pot files, po files, mo files, all these things, which

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:09.279
you don't really need to understand that much to add translations to your package. So over

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:13.880
the last couple of months, I've been working on a package called PoTools. The goal is to

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:17.559
really eliminate as much of those frictions as possible to make it easier to add translations

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:21.399
to the packages. And as of right now, there's only one user-facing function. It's called

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:27.199
translate package. And it does all the legwork for you of adding together all those get text

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:31.520
spacing utilities and just walks you through adding translations to all the messages it

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:38.960
finds with your package. So with that in mind, we really need to think about how to set your

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:43.839
package up to be translated in the first place. There are some general rules about how to

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:47.919
do development on your project that will make it easier for translation. The first

00:02:47.919 --> 00:02:54.960
one is about templating. Here, the stop message that we see, it's something very common to

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:59.279
see and it's used all the time in my own development. But in terms of translation, it makes things

00:02:59.279 --> 00:03:04.559
a bit harder. What a translator would see from the first instance is three strings.

00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:09.759
Sound, columns, comma, but, and are needed. And out of context, those things are very

00:03:09.759 --> 00:03:14.639
hard to translate. And there's some issues with duplication where it would be even harder

00:03:14.639 --> 00:03:20.639
to translate. If it's in the templated form, the translator is free to rearrange things,

00:03:20.639 --> 00:03:24.160
which will have to be done in, for example, Japanese, which has a totally different grammar.

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:31.839
And, yeah, just the templated form makes it a lot easier for translators to really make the

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:36.720
message appear as it naturally would in their own language. It's a similar thing for

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:40.479
pluralization. English is blessed to have a pretty simple pluralization system.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:47.759
When n equals 1 in this message, the error would become found an issue. When n is different from 1,

00:03:47.759 --> 00:03:53.919
the error message would become found some issues. And, for example, East Asian languages is

00:03:53.919 --> 00:03:58.399
typically even easier. There's not really any pluralization in the first place. But for some

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:04.880
languages like Slovenian and Arabic, there are up to four or even six types of pluralization that

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:10.960
have to be handled by translators. And for that, there's this nget text function that

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:16.880
is part of base R that you provided the number and some template translations and then your

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:21.440
translator would help do the legwork of providing what the translations should be based on what n

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:28.559
is. And that's all we'll have time for today in the lightning talk. So, thanks to everybody.

00:04:28.559 --> 00:04:33.279
Thanks to RStudio for the invite. And thanks to all the contributors to the languages. And

00:04:33.279 --> 00:04:35.279
thank you.

